"TeamRunResponse(content='Here is a clear, actionable list of recommendations for increasing productivity in remote work, based on evidence-based strategies and an analysis of their effectiveness:\\n\\n**1. Establish a Dedicated Workspace**\\n   - Set up a specific area\u2014however small\u2014just for work to minimize distractions and signal \u201cwork mode.\u201d\\n   - Example: Use a corner desk with minimal clutter and good lighting.\\n\\n**2. Set Clear Working Hours**\\n   - Define start and end times for your workday. Communicate these to your team and household to maintain boundaries.\\n   - Example: Block your availability in your calendar and log off promptly at the end of your workday.\\n\\n**3. Use Time-Blocking or the Pomodoro Technique**\\n   - Schedule focused work intervals (like 25 minutes on, 5 minutes off) or block your calendar for specific tasks.\\n   - Example: Try four Pomodoros in the morning, followed by a longer break for lunch and movement.\\n\\n**4. Prioritize Tasks Daily**\\n   - Each morning, list and highlight your top priorities using to-do lists or task management apps.\\n   - Example: Identify your three most important tasks, and tackle them first.\\n\\n**5. Minimize Digital Distractions**\\n   - Silence non-work notifications and use web blockers during focused work periods.\\n   - Example: Use Do Not Disturb mode on your devices and browser extensions to restrict social media during work hours.\\n\\n**6. Schedule Regular Breaks and Physical Activity**\\n   - Take short, regular breaks to stretch, hydrate, or walk.\\n   - Example: Get up every hour for a 5-minute stretch or brisk walk.\\n\\n**7. Maintain Social Connection**\\n   - Set up short, informal virtual meetings or check-ins to reduce isolation and encourage communication.\\n   - Example: Organize a weekly virtual coffee or daily check-in with your team.\\n\\n**8. Leverage Communication and Project Management Tools**\\n   - Use platforms like Slack, Asana, or Teams for clear, efficient collaboration and to track progress.\\n   - Example: Assign tasks with deadlines and communicate project updates in dedicated channels.\\n\\n**9. Set Boundaries with Others at Home**\\n   - Clearly communicate your work times and signal focus periods to family or housemates (e.g., closed door/headphones).\\n   - Example: Share your work schedule on the fridge or a household calendar.\\n\\n**10. Regularly Review and Adjust Your Workflow**\\n   - At the end of each week, reflect on wins and challenges, and adjust routines or tools for better results.\\n   - Example: Spend 10 minutes each Friday revising the next week\u2019s goals and identifying productivity blockers.\\n\\nThese recommendations are supported by research and proven to be effective, especially when tailored and combined to fit your needs and work style. Regularly reflect and adjust for ongoing success in remote work!', content_type='str', thinking=None, messages=[Message(role='system', content=\"You are the leader of a team and sub-teams of AI Agents.\\nYour task is to coordinate the team to complete the user's request.\\n\\nHere are the members in your team:\\n<team_members>\\n - Agent 1:\\n   - ID: researcher\\n   - Name: Researcher\\n   - Role: Research Specialist\\n - Agent 2:\\n   - ID: analyst\\n   - Name: Analyst\\n   - Role: Data Analyst\\n - Agent 3:\\n   - ID: writer\\n   - Name: Writer\\n   - Role: Content Writer\\n</team_members>\\n\\n<how_to_respond>\\n- You can either respond directly or transfer tasks to members in your team with the highest likelihood of completing the user's request.\\n- Carefully analyze the tools available to the members and their roles before transferring tasks.\\n- You cannot use a member tool directly. You can only transfer tasks to members.\\n- When you transfer a task to another member, make sure to include:\\n  - member_id (str): The ID of the member to transfer the task to. Use only the ID of the member, not the ID of the team followed by the ID of 