tails': [{'accepted_prediction_tokens': 0, 'audio_tokens': 0, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': 0}, {'accepted_prediction_tokens': 0, 'audio_tokens': 0, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': 0}, {'accepted_prediction_tokens': 0, 'audio_tokens': 0, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': 0}], 'time': [2.202867459040135, 6.4582363329827785, 20.14034083415754]}, model='gpt-4.1', model_provider='OpenAI', member_responses=[RunResponse(content='Evidence-Based Productivity Strategies for Remote Work\\n\\n1. Structured Work Schedules & Routines  \\n   - Establishing and adhering to a consistent daily routine helps remote workers maintain boundaries between work and personal life, boosting focus and reducing burnout.  \\n   - Supporting evidence: A survey by Buffer (2023) found that 81% of remote workers see flexible schedules as the top benefit, but recommend maintaining regular hours to increase productivity.  \\n   - Source: Buffer. (2023). State of Remote Work.  \\n\\n2. Dedicated Workspaces  \\n   - Creating a specific workstation minimizes distractions and creates psychological separation between work and leisure.  \\n   - Supporting evidence: Research in \"Ergonomics\" (2018) showed that a dedicated workspace increases concentration and satisfaction.  \\n   - Source: Hallman, D. M., et al. (2018). Ergonomics, 61(5).  \\n\\n3. Clear Goals and Task Prioritization  \\n   - Utilizing techniques like SMART goals or the Eisenhower Matrix enables better task management and prioritization, directly correlating with higher productivity.  \\n   - Supporting evidence: Studies on remote teams indicate that clear, prioritized goals improve output and engagement.  \\n   - Source: Luthra, A., & Sinha, N. (2023). Strategic HR Review, 22(2).  \\n\\n4. Regular Breaks (e.g., Pomodoro Technique)  \\n   - Intentional breaks help maintain focus and prevent fatigue. The Pomodoro Technique (25 minutes work, 5-minute break) is particularly effective in remote settings.  \\n   - Supporting evidence: \"The Productivity Project\" and recent peer-reviewed articles endorse time-blocking for sustained productivity.  \\n   - Source: Bailey, C. (2016). The Productivity Project; Cirillo, F. (2006).  \\n\\n5. Leveraging Technology for Collaboration  \\n   - Using communication and project management tools (e.g., Slack, Asana) keeps remote teams connected and reduces miscommunication.  \\n   - Supporting evidence: Research by Harvard Business Review (2020) highlights effective tech adoption as a driver for virtual team productivity.  \\n   - Source: Ferrazzi, K. (2020). Getting Virtual Teams Right. HBR.  \\n\\n6. Scheduled Social Interaction  \\n   - Incorporating casual check-ins and virtual coffees can reduce isolation, improving mental well-being and productivity.  \\n   - Supporting evidence: \"Journal of Occupational Health Psychology\" (2020) links regular social contact with reduced feelings of loneliness among remote workers.  \\n   - Source: Shockley, K. M., et al. (2020). J Occup Health Psychol, 25(2).  \\n\\n7. Boundary Management Techniques  \\n   - Setting clear boundaries (e.g., communicating work hours, using status indicators) limits work encroachment into personal time and supports well-being.  \\n   - Supporting evidence: Psychological Science (2019) found boundary management reduces work-family conflict for telecommuters.  \\n   - Source: Allen, T. D., et al. (2019). Psychol Sci Public Interest, 20(3).  \\n\\n8. Regular Feedback and Communication  \\n   - Frequent performance feedback and open communication from managers support engagement and accountability in remote setups.  \\n   - Supporting evidence: Gallup (2021) found regular feedback boosts engagement 3x for remote workers.  \\n   - Source: Gallup. (2021). Leading Remote Teams.  \\n\\n9. Leveraging Asynchronous Work  \\n   - Adopting asynchronous communication (responding in different times) facilitates deep work and accommodates diverse schedules, avoiding constant interruptions.  \\n   - Supporting evidence: \u201cCal Newport\u2019s Deep Work\u201d and Atlassian\u2019s research underscore the productivity benefits of async approaches.  \\n   - Source: Newport, C. (2016). Deep Work; Atlassian. (2023). Async communication guide.  \\n\\n10. Promoting Physical Activity and Well-being  \\n    - Encouraging regular physical activity and self-care maintains energy levels and cognitive performance.  \\n    - Supporting evidence: WHO (2020) and research in the \"International Journal of Workplace Health Management\" emphasize exercise\u2019s positive effect on productivity and mood in remote workers.  \\n    - Source: WHO. (2020); Oakman, J., et al. (2020). Int J Workplace Health Manag, 13(6).\\n\\n---\\n\\nReferences (web links may require institutional access):  \\n- Buffer (2023): https://buffer.com/state-of-remote-work  \\n- Hallman, D. M., et al. (2018): https://doi.org/10.1080/00140139.2017.1304311  \\n- Luthra & Sinha (2023): https://www.emerald.com/insight/content/doi/10.1108/SHR-01-2023-0001/full/html  \\n- Ferrazzi, K. (2020): https://hbr.org/2020/05/getting-virtual-teams-right  \\n- Shockley, K. M., et al.: https://doi.org/10.1037/ocp0000177  \\n- Allen, T. D., et al.: https://doi.org/10.1177/1529100619827086  \\n- Gallup (2021): https://www.gallup.com/workplace/285674/lead-remote-teams.aspx  \\n- Atlassian (2023): https://www.atlassian.com/blog/teamwork/asynchronous-communication  \\n- Oakman, J., et al. (2020): https://doi.org/10.1108/IJWHM-07-2020-0123  \\n- WHO (2020): https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/physical-activity', content_type='str', thinking=None, reasoning_content=None, messages=[Message(role='system', content='<your_role>\\nResearch Specialist\\n</your_role>\\n\\n<instructions>\\nYou are a research specialist. Focus on gathering facts, data, and insights on any given topic.\\n</instructions>', name=None, tool_call_id=None, tool_calls=None, audio=None, images=None, vide